WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:19.800
All right, here we are at layer number two, which is the data link layer, appropriate

00:19.800 --> 00:39.880
name. All right, here we are at layer number two, which is the data link layer, appropriate

00:39.880 --> 00:47.040
name for this layer, data link really means that it links the data between the two adjacent

00:47.040 --> 00:54.320
layers that are next to it. So if you know what the layer below the data link layer is,

00:54.320 --> 00:59.880
that's the physical layer. And then above the data link layer we have the network layer.

00:59.880 --> 01:06.160
The data link layer allows those two adjacent layers to actually talk to each other. Because

01:06.160 --> 01:11.880
when you look at what the network layer works with, it works with data grams and packets,

01:11.880 --> 01:17.800
that's not what the physical layer works with. The physical layer as we've already learned can

01:17.800 --> 01:24.000
only work with bits, zeros and ones. So the layer in between, which is this layer, guess what it

01:24.000 --> 01:32.960
does? It takes information from the network layer as data grams and formats those as bits so that

01:32.960 --> 01:38.480
the physical layer can work with them as bits. At the other end, guess what the data link layer

01:38.480 --> 01:45.280
does? It takes the bits of information from the physical layer and formats them in such a way so

01:45.280 --> 01:51.920
that the network layer can work with them as packets and data grams. So it really allows the two

01:51.920 --> 01:58.720
adjacent layers to it to be able to talk to each other. Think of it as the translator or the

01:58.720 --> 02:05.840
go between that allows the two adjacent layers to talk to each other. Now at this, at this layer is

02:05.840 --> 02:14.080
also where we reference what are called your physical unique address across a network. In other

02:14.080 --> 02:20.720
words, a network is made up of different devices that are connected to each other, but the network

02:20.720 --> 02:29.280
needs to understand each of those devices uniquely. So there needs to be some sort of unique physical

02:29.280 --> 02:35.280
address that the network can reference for each of the devices that are connected to each other.

02:35.600 --> 02:41.920
This is called the MAC address. The MAC address is really a function of your network card that

02:41.920 --> 02:48.720
allows you to connect to the network and every device connected to a network has to have a unique

02:48.720 --> 02:56.080
physical MAC address that is referenced here at layer two. And it looks something like you see

02:56.080 --> 03:03.520
there on your screen, but what the industry needs to make sure is that each of these MAC addresses

03:03.520 --> 03:10.320
are unique as they come from the manufacturers. So there is a system by which this is insured.

03:10.320 --> 03:16.080
For example, the first number of bits for your MAC address relates to the vendor.

03:17.280 --> 03:22.480
And so that would be unique to a vendor. And then the next set of bits is something else that

03:22.480 --> 03:28.560
ensures uniqueness and so on so that we can have network cards and devices that come from different

03:28.560 --> 03:35.040
manufacturers. They all need to have unique physical addresses because if you didn't,

03:35.040 --> 03:42.000
that would confuse the network every device or node connected to a network has to have a unique

03:42.000 --> 03:48.960
physical address that is referenced here as a MAC address. Although when we get to the network

03:48.960 --> 03:56.240
layer, you'll see that the logical addressing in networking is actually done at the network layer,

03:56.240 --> 04:02.480
not at the data link layer, which was what we're talking about here. The data link layer simply

04:02.480 --> 04:09.440
provides the physical unique address through the MAC address itself. Now here's where we also talk

04:09.440 --> 04:15.600
about the two types of networks that exist because if you remember what a network is, it's a bunch

04:15.600 --> 04:22.960
of devices that are connected to each other. Now how we communicate with other devices is the

04:22.960 --> 04:28.960
difference between circuit switch networks and packet switch networks. Those are the two types

04:28.960 --> 04:35.760
of networks that can exist. Now the easiest way to think of circuit switch networks is the

04:35.760 --> 04:42.560
phone network itself, the PSTN, the public switch telephone network or what some telephone people

04:42.560 --> 04:50.800
call the POTS, the plain old telephone system. That network has been around for over 100 years in

04:50.800 --> 04:56.960
some cases. But what they figured out back in those days was that the best way to carry the

04:56.960 --> 05:04.000
human voice, which is what this network has been built to do, are actually analog frequencies,

05:04.000 --> 05:11.680
I think, between 4,000 hertz and 6,000 hertz. But this network has been built to handle analog

05:11.680 --> 05:17.520
frequencies because that's the best way to represent your voice. But in order to be able to

05:17.520 --> 05:24.160
communicate across this network and here's why it's called a circuit switch network, two devices

05:24.160 --> 05:30.800
that need to communicate with each other have to actually establish a circuit or a connection between

05:30.800 --> 05:38.000
them. Now that connection can be either physical or logical, but we need to establish a full duplex

05:38.000 --> 05:43.600
type of connection, which means we can talk in both directions at the same time. Our animation

05:43.760 --> 05:48.880
here I think does a pretty good job of showing what this looks like. There is a series of devices

05:48.880 --> 05:56.240
along the way called switches across the telephone network that will ultimately establish a connection

05:56.240 --> 06:02.320
between you and that other person that you want to talk to. And of course what you do is you dial

06:02.320 --> 06:09.200
their number, but that activates those switches across the way that will ultimately establish

06:09.200 --> 06:15.120
a logical or physical connection so that now we can talk back and forth in both directions.

06:15.120 --> 06:20.720
That's what we call a full duplex type of connection. We can both talk to each other at the same

06:20.720 --> 06:25.920
time, even though if we did that, we wouldn't understand each other, but that is possible. That's

06:25.920 --> 06:32.800
what we call full duplex type of connection. This is what the telephone network is and in fact,

06:32.800 --> 06:38.800
if you think of the telephone network, it is a perfect example of a circuit switch network.

06:38.800 --> 06:45.920
The telephone network. Now, if you remember back in the old days, when data started to become

06:45.920 --> 06:52.960
something that was really important to organizations, the only way that you could connect remotely

06:52.960 --> 06:59.360
to your internal network was to actually use the only network that was available for us to do that.

06:59.360 --> 07:05.600
And that was the telephone network, but the problem with the telephone network is that it has

07:05.600 --> 07:13.200
a limitation because it is a analog technology. It was built to carry the human voice and the

07:13.200 --> 07:20.080
best way to do that is to use analog technologies. So the only way that you could carry data across

07:20.080 --> 07:28.480
it was to take your digital signals that computers use and turn them into analog so that they could

07:28.480 --> 07:34.960
be carried across the analog telephone network. And then at the other end, you would have a similar

07:35.040 --> 07:42.320
device that would take that analog signal and turn it back into digital. And of course, those devices

07:42.320 --> 07:49.600
are called modems, aren't they? In fact, the word modem comes from modulation, demodulation,

07:49.600 --> 07:55.760
which does exactly what we just described. It takes your digital signals, turns them into analog

07:55.760 --> 08:01.520
so that they can be carried across the analog telephone network. And then, of course, at the other

08:01.520 --> 08:06.240
end, we turn it back into digital. Now, there's always been a problem with this. And that is,

08:06.240 --> 08:12.720
there's a limitation in the speeds and the bandwidth, for example, that we can host. And that is

08:12.720 --> 08:20.400
because the analog telephone network is analog. It's backbone is analog. And so we've always had

08:20.400 --> 08:27.440
that limitation, which I think is 56,000 bits per second. And a lot of people ask a question,

08:27.440 --> 08:34.640
why haven't we improved modem technology to give us faster speeds? Well, we have, in fact,

08:34.640 --> 08:41.840
in fact, all of you probably use DSL modems and cable modems that handle much faster speeds.

08:42.320 --> 08:49.280
But the problem with the telephone network is not in the modem. It's in the network itself.

08:49.280 --> 08:55.760
That's why we still have that limitation with modems. So obviously, when data started to

08:55.760 --> 09:02.640
become a requirement, we couldn't use modems anymore because of that limitation. So that forced

09:02.640 --> 09:10.560
companies to build separate and specific data networks to handle the quantity of data, the speeds

09:10.560 --> 09:17.120
that we required today. And those are called packet switched networks. So the easiest way to think

09:17.120 --> 09:23.280
of this is that all data networks are packet switched. The way this works is if we need to send

09:23.280 --> 09:29.680
information between devices, we're not going to establish a circuit or connection first.

09:29.680 --> 09:36.160
What I do if I need to send you information as I take that information and I break it up into

09:36.160 --> 09:43.440
manageable chunks. And then I individually address each of those chunks. And then I send them along

09:43.440 --> 09:51.040
the way. Now those chunks, called packets or datagrams typically, will travel in different directions.

09:51.520 --> 09:57.280
You know, they may arrive in a different order than they were sent. Some of them may not even arrive.

09:57.280 --> 10:03.920
But you know, basically we have the technology to be able to do that, receive those datagrams and packets

10:03.920 --> 10:10.000
and reconstruct them into what the original data look like. That's what all data networks do.

10:10.000 --> 10:16.800
And because we break things up into manageable chunks that can be each individually addressed

10:16.880 --> 10:24.800
and sent along the way, these are called packet switch networks. All data networks work this way.

10:24.800 --> 10:33.040
All data networks are packet switch networks because they can handle the high volumes and bandwidths

10:33.040 --> 10:39.040
and speeds that we need today for the applications that really data networks are built for today.

10:39.040 --> 10:46.400
Here's just a basic summary of the two types of networks that can exist. And pretty

10:46.400 --> 10:51.760
intuitively you can see the difference here and what they're typically used for. Just remember

10:51.760 --> 10:57.360
that circuit switched is the voice network. All data networks are packet switch because they

10:57.360 --> 11:03.760
can give us the speeds and the bandwidth and what we need today for our applications.

11:03.760 --> 11:10.320
Now across data networks though, sometimes you may want connections that are established on demand

11:11.040 --> 11:18.560
or for example, maybe companies need to link, you know, a data network in one location to a data

11:18.560 --> 11:24.960
network in another location permanently. Let's say we are a company that has offices in two

11:24.960 --> 11:32.080
different cities. And so we may want to link those two offices or data networks together permanently.

11:32.080 --> 11:38.320
That's what we call permanent virtual circuits. Those are data network connections that are

11:38.320 --> 11:45.040
established typically across what we call wide area network technologies that are offered to us

11:45.040 --> 11:52.320
by our providers. We'll talk more about that later on. Whereas a switched virtual circuit is one

11:52.320 --> 11:58.080
that we establish on demand. And then once we're finished, we tear it down. Perfect example of that

11:58.080 --> 12:04.000
would be a VPN connection. So that's the difference between the two types of connections that we can

12:04.000 --> 12:14.960
establish across data networks or packet switch networks.

